<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910122-0060</DOCNO><DOCID>910122-0060.</DOCID><HL>   Raytheon Net Rose   4.8% in Quarter, Aided   By Patriot Missiles</HL><DATE>01/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13</SO><CO>   RTN</CO><IN>DIVERSIFIED TECHNOLOGY (DTC)EARNINGS (ERN)AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><LP>   LEXINGTON, Mass. -- Raytheon Co., aided by governmentcontracts for its Patriot missiles, reported a 4.8% rise innet income and a 9.5% sales gain in the fourth quarter.   Net income at the defense electronics concern increased to$143.6 million, or $2.20 a share, from $137 million, or $2.07a share, a year earlier. Results include a charge of $11.5million from the closing of a facility. Sales rose to $2.46billion from $2.24 billion.</LP><TEXT>   Raytheon, whose Patriot missiles have been credited withdeflecting Iraqi Scud missile attacks against Saudi Arabia,said its electronics division was its largest businesssegment in 1990, accounting for $5.5 billion in sales.   Raytheon's aircraft and energy services segments alsoperformed well, with aircraft sales increasing 17% from 1989to $1.07 billion and energy sales rising 14% to $993 million.   The company's appliances segment, however, reported thatsales dropped 2.7% to $1.04 billion due to the recession. Thesegment reported a pretax loss of $8 million due to losses atits Caloric division resulting from excess capacity and theclosing of its Topton, Pa., manufacturing facility. Caloric'sloss more than offset profitable performances at its Amanaand Speed Queen divisions, Raytheon said.   Raytheon's backlog fell 8.2% to $8.81 billion from $9.59billion at year-end 1989, including a $400 million drop ingovernment orders.   For the year, Raytheon reported a 5.4% increase in netincome to $557.3 million, or $8.53 a share, from $528.8million, or $8.01 a share, in 1989. Sales rose 5.4% to $9.27billion from $8.8 billion.   Raytheon shares closed at $74.625, up $4.50, in New YorkStock Exchange composite trading.</TEXT></DOC>